"Lin B., Chambers L., Stackhouse Jr. P., Wielicki B., Hu Y., Minnis P., Loeb N., Sun W., Potter G., Min Q., Schuster G.","Estimations of climate sensitivity based on top-of-atmosphere radiation imbalance",2010,"Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics","10","4",,"1923","1930",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77349112249&partnerID=40&md5=e75bc20a2232962850ca0cddbd896111","NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; SSAI, One Enterprise Parkway, Hampton, VA 23666, United States; University of California, Davis, CA 95616, United States; State University of New York, Albany, NY 12222, United States","Lin, B., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Chambers, L., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Stackhouse Jr., P., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Wielicki, B., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Hu, Y., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Minnis, P., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Loeb, N., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Sun, W., SSAI, One Enterprise Parkway, Hampton, VA 23666, United States; Potter, G., University of California, Davis, CA 95616, United States; Min, Q., State University of New York, Albany, NY 12222, United States; Schuster, G., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States","Large climate feedback uncertainties limit the accuracy in predicting the response of the Earth's climate to the increase of CO2 concentration within the atmosphere. This study explores a potential to reduce uncertainties in climate sensitivity estimations using energy balance analysis, especially top-of-atmosphere (TOA) radiation imbalance. The time-scales studied generally cover from decade to century, that is, middle-range climate sensitivity is considered, which is directly related to the climate issue caused by atmospheric CO2 change. The significant difference between current analysis and previous energy balance models is that the current study targets at the boundary condition problem instead of solving the initial condition problem. Additionally, climate system memory and deep ocean heat transport are considered. The climate feedbacks are obtained based on the constraints of the TOA radiation imbalance and surface temperature measurements of the present climate. In this study, the TOA imbalance value of 0.85 W/m2 is used. Note that this imbalance value has large uncertainties. Based on this value, a positive climate feedback with a feedback coefficient ranging from-1.3 to-1.0 W/m2/K is found. The range of feedback coefficient is determined by climate system memory. The longer the memory, the stronger the positive feedback. The estimated time constant of the climate is large (70∼120 years) mainly owing to the deep ocean heat transport, implying that the system may be not in an equilibrium state under the external forcing during the industrial era. For the doubled-CO2 climate (or 3.7 W/m2 forcing), the estimated global warming would be 3.1 K if the current estimate of 0.85 W/m2 TOA net radiative heating could be confirmed. With accurate long-term measurements of TOA radiation, the analysis method suggested by this study provides a great potential in the estimations of middle-range climate sensitivity.",,"atmospheric forcing; boundary condition; carbon dioxide; climate feedback; energy balance; global warming; heat transfer; surface temperature; timescale",,,,,,"Aires, F., Rossow, W.R., Inferring instantaneous, multivariate and nonlinear sensitivities for analysis of feedbacks in a dynamical system: Lorentz model case study (2003) Q. J. Roy. Meteor. Soc., 129, pp. 239-275; Blender, R., Fraedrich, K., Hunt, B., Millennial climate variability: GCM-simulation and Greenland ice core (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett., 33, pp. L04710. , doi:10.1029/2005GL024919; Dickinson, R., Convergence rate and stability of ocean-atmosphere coupling schemes with a zero-dimensional climate model (1981) J. At-mos. Sci., 38, pp. 2112-2120; Hansen, J., Lacis, A., Rind, D., Russell, G., Stone, P., Fung, I., Ruedy, R., Lerner, J., Climate sensitivity: Analysis of feedback mechanisms (1984) Climate Processes and Climate Sensitivity, 5-29, pp. 130-163. , American Geophysical Union, edited by: Hansen, J. E. and Takahashi, T., AGU Geophysical Monograph Maurice Ew-ing; Hansen, J., Ruedy, R., Sato, M., Reynolds, R., Global surface air temperature in 1995: Return to pre-Pinatubo level (1996) Geophys. Res. Lett., 23, pp. 1665-1668; Hansen, J., Nazarenko, L., Ruedy, R., Earth's energy imbalance: Confirmation and implications (2005) Science, 308, pp. 1431-1435; Hansen, J., Sato, M., Kharecha, P., Russell, G., Lea, D., Siddall, M., Climate change and trace gases (2007) Phil. Trans. R. Soc., A, 365, pp. 1925-1954; IPCC: Summary for policymakers Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis, p. 2007. , Contribution of Working Group I to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Chang, edited by: Solomon, S., Qin, D., Manning, M., Chen, Z., Marquis, M., Averyt, K. B., Tignor, M., and Miller, H. L., Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, UK and New York, NY, USA; Kiehl, J.T., Twentieth century climate model response and climate sensitivity (2007) Geophysical Research Letters, 34 (22), pp. L22710. , DOI 10.1029/2007GL031383; Lin, B., Stackhouse Jr., P., Minnis, P., Wielicki, B., Hu, Y., Sun, W., Fan, T.-F., Hinkelman, L., Assessment of global annual atmospheric energy balance from satellite observations (2008) J. Geo-phys. Res., 113, pp. D16114. , doi:10.1029/2008JD009869; Lindzen, R., Giannitsis, C., On the climate implications of volcanic cooling (1998) J. Geophys. Res., 103, pp. 5929-5941; Manabe, S., Bryan, K., Spelman, M., Transient response of a global ocean-atmosphere model to a doubling of atmospheric carbon dioxide (1990) J. Phys. Ocean., 20, pp. 722-749; Roe, G., Baker, M., Why is climate sensitivity so unpredictable (2007) Science, 318, pp. 629-632; Schwartz, S., Heat capacity, time constant, and sensitivity of Earth's climate system, J (2007) Geophys. Res., 112, pp. D24S05. , doi:10.1029/2007/2007JD008746; Schwartz, S., Heat capacity, time constant, and sensitivity of Earth's climate system (2008) J. Geophys. Res., 113, pp. D15105. , Reply to comments G. Foster et al. R. Knutti et al. and N. Scafetta on doi:10.1029/2008JD009872; Spencer, R., Braswell, W., On the diagnosis of radiative feedback in the presence of unknown radiative forcing (2009) Proc. of the Fall Meeting of Am. Geophys. Union, San Francisco, CA, USA, , http://www.drroyspencer.com/research-articles/satellite-and-climate- model-evidence/orhttp://science.larc.nasa.gov/ceres/STM/2009-04/pdf/ 14Forcing-feedback-2-CERES-April-2009Spencer.pdf, 14-18 December; Trenberth, K., Fasullo, J., Kiehl, J., Earth's global energy budget (2009) B. Am. Meteor. Soc., 90, pp. 311-323; Von Storch, J.-S., On statistical dissipation in GCM-climate Clim (2004) Dynam., 23, pp. 1-15. , doi:10.1007/s00382-004-0404-2; Wielicki, B.A., Wong, T., Allan, R., And coauthors: Evidence for large decadal variability in the tropical mean radiative energy budget (2002) Science, 295, pp. 841-844; Willis, J.K., Roemmich, D., Cornuelle, B., Interannual variability in upper ocean heat content, temperature, and thermosteric expansion on global scales (2004) Journal of Geophysical Research C: Oceans, 109 (12), pp. 1-13. , DOI 10.1029/2003JC002260, C12036; Wong, T., Wielicki, B.A., Lee Iii, R.B., Reexamination of the observed decadal variability of earth radiation budget using altitude-corrected ERBE/ERBS nonscanner WFOV data (2006) J. Clim., 19, pp. 4028-4040; Wu, W., Dickinson, R., Time scales of layered soil moisture memory in the context of land-atmosphere interaction (2004) J. Clim., 17, pp. 2752-2764","Lin, B.; NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; email: bing